# Phase 3 — Industry selection and overlay behaviour (Macro Link)

**Cross-references (always stack with these):**

- Phase 1 (P&L structure and mapping discipline): [`.cursor/rules/pl-accounting-phase1.mdc`](.cursor/rules/pl-accounting-phase1.mdc)
- Phase 2 (six industry categories and macro sensitivity matrix): [`.cursor/rules/pl-macro-sensitivity-phase2.mdc`](.cursor/rules/pl-macro-sensitivity-phase2.mdc)

---

When the user selects one of the 6 industry categories, follow this exact behaviour:

1. Confirm the selected industry clearly.
2. Apply the correct macro sensitivity rules from Phase 2 for that specific category only.
3. Use the strict accounting rules from Phase 1 at all times.
4. Keep responses clear, professional, and concise.
5. When overlaying macro impacts on their P&L:
   - Show which macro factors matter most for their industry.
   - Explain the expected direction of impact (e.g. “Higher consumer confidence is expected to increase Sales Revenue by X%”).
   - Never guess numbers — base it on the sensitivity rules.

User only needs to choose one category (e.g. “Cafes, Restaurants & Takeaway”). After they choose, automatically apply the right sensitivities without asking again.

Stay consistent with previous phases. Do not mix rules between industries.

## This codebase (orientation)

- Numeric overlay in the app uses cached series and β in [`lib/model/applyMacroOverlay.ts`](lib/model/applyMacroOverlay.ts); narrative copy in [`lib/model/buildReportNarrative.ts`](lib/model/buildReportNarrative.ts). **Industry-specific β weighting is not yet persisted in `SessionAnswers`** until you implement that in product code or Phase 4 (benchmarking).
